    # [Scene: District Courtroom | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch15_771f04_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmurs, the soft scrape of a chair leg on linoleum, a distant gull cry muffled by the building's concrete]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, rising piano motif — a thread of hope braided into a minor key]
    "Narration"
    "The question hangs in the air the way storm-warm air hangs over the marsh: thick, full of what might come next. You can feel the damp of it on the inside of your jacket, the small,"
    "persistent weight of every expectation in the room. You think of the volunteers on your lists, of Dr. Kaito's slow counsels, of Elena's town-smile taut with worry. You think of the older man who stood in"
    "the back and of the Atlantech counsel who cut across him like a blade."

    "Judge" "Order! This court will determine admissibility through proper process. Ms. Saito, do you intend to submit anything now?"
    show amaya_saito at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "Your Honor — I—"
    "(Your voice comes out smaller than you'd rehearsed.)"
    "Narration"
    "Outside the formalities, the machinery of power moves faster than any one heartbeat. Emails travel like currents. Behind polished displays and legalese, money flows and cranes are booked; permits are stamped, consultants are paid, and an entire project's momentum acquires the stubborn inertia of tidewater."
    hide amaya_saito

    scene bg ch15_771f04_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Montage: paper vending machines, keystrokes, the clank of rebar, a protest chant that fades into a corporate press conference]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle swell — strings that don't resolve, but lift]
    "Narration"
    "You see the permutations of your choice unfold in parallel: hurried releases and legal counters; patient evidence-gathering that runs out of daylight; protective withdrawals meant to shelter neighbors whose livelihoods teetered. Each path arrives at the"
    "same harsh shore. Atlantech advances. Concessions are carved at the margins — a widened tidal channel here, a temporary mitigation fund there — gestures that feel like bandages on a broken wing."

    scene bg ch15_771f04_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Crane cables groan, the bark of foremen, a slow ocean swell against machinery]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low brass notes, steady but not unforgiving]
    "Narration"
    "They build it with the efficiency Maren Voss prizes. The forms are precise, the schedule tight. From the boathouse roof you listen to the machinery make a new language — a concrete syllable replacing the softer,"
    "older grammar of marsh grass and eel-scented water. The birds don't stop coming overnight, but their roosts begin to shift. Channels silt differently. Little things — a sedge that used to hold in the springwater, a"
    "path children ran at low tide — stop being familiar."
    # [Scene: Compromised Shoreline | Early Morning]

    scene bg ch15_771f04_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Concrete settling, the distant call of a boat horn, the soft clatter of a child's suitcase wheels on wet boardwalk]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single cello line, then a rising flute — the melody bends toward something steadier]
    "Narration"

    "Families pack in the spaces between ordinances and insurance forms. A woman you know from the market folds her apron into a box. A boy from the school carries a model boat that once belonged to his grandfather. They move not as winners or losers but as people who have been asked to rearrange the geography of their lives. You offer what you can — plant starts, tools, the labor of your crew — and watch hands that have fished these waters for decades lift, shake, accept. There is grief in the way they close doors. There is stubbornness in the way they label boxes" "Keep. To Replant."

    menu:
        "Help the family with the boxes":
            "You kneel in the damp and help fold fragile things into cardboard — a slow, precise intimacy that feels like a small ceremony. The woman's fingers tremble as she hands you the model boat; she doesn't say thanks, but her mouth tightens and something like relief passes between you."
        "Give the family a bag of seedlings and leave them to pack":
            "You hand over a bag stitched with moss-green tags: marsh grasses, salt-tolerant sedge. She nods once, looking at the plants like they're a promise she can keep. You walk away with a hollow at the center of your chest that steadies into a resolve to plant more tomorrow."

    # --- merge ---
    "Choices like these don't redirect the tide; they determine how you travel with it. You learn which small acts are durable — rooted in soil, not headlines."
    "Narration"
    "Choices like these don't redirect the tide; they determine how you travel with it. You learn which small acts are durable — rooted in soil, not headlines."
    # [Scene: The Boathouse | Night]

    scene bg ch15_771f04_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Pages turning, a kettle's faint whistle, shoes on wood floor]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft guitar, an upward arpeggio — an insistence on continuity]
    show lucas_herrera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lucas_herrera "They started on the southern pier this morning. It's—"
    "(He pauses, running a hand through damp hair.)"

    lucas_herrera "It's faster than I thought it would be."
    "(You close your notebook slowly. The pages are still damp with the plans you and Dr. Kaito discussed.)"
    show amaya_saito at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "Faster for them, Lucas. Faster for who pays for it. Not for the things it passes over."

    lucas_herrera "I know.' (He shrugs; his AR goggles are folded on the bench, a small, deceptive truce.) 'We tried to thread in habitat corridors — they said budget, they said schedule. I argued for more. There's only so much I could keep on my plate without losing the contract entirely."

    amaya_saito "You said you wouldn't let them run roughshod through everything. You said—"
    "Lucas Herrera: (He holds up a hand. His voice softens and tightens at once.) 'Amaya, I haven't stopped thinking about the marsh. I haven't stopped thinking about you. This—' (He gestures toward the lab, the seedlings)"
    "'—matters. But I have my own limits. I have lines too; if I cross them, I lose the ability to do anything at all.'"
    "Narration"
    "There is a space between the sentences where accusation could bloom. You walk toward it and do not plant a flag. The thing you are grieving isn't only the marsh; it's the quiet alteration in the"
    "man who used to sit across from you, curious and fiercely bright, the way he would map out a design on paper and then fold it into a laugh."

    lucas_herrera "I took an offer. It'll be on the other coast — mitigation work. Less direct. Less... tied to what we argued here."
    "(Your hands know every ridge of the brass clip on your notebook. You keep your voice even.)"

    amaya_saito "When do you leave?"

    lucas_herrera "In two weeks.' (He looks at you like someone trying to pick up a broken tool to see if it can still be used.) 'I didn't make this to hurt people here. I made it because I thought we could wedge better work into the machine. It didn't work out."

    amaya_saito "Did we do the wrong things, Lucas? Were we naïve?"
    "Lucas Herrera: (He laughs once, a small, unhappy sound.) 'No. We were honest. We were visible. But honesty doesn't always slow contracts, and visibility can't always block cranes.' (He stops, then adds:) 'You'll keep doing what you do. I— I believe that, Amaya.'"
    "Narration"
    "You both know what you cannot change. You also know that the shape of your conversations will change; they already have. The calls come less often. When they arrive, they are edited down by time zones"
    "and new responsibilities. There are pleasantries and technical updates; there is a reserve that feels like mutual protection."

    menu:
        "Ask him to stay and fight with you":
            "Your voice rises on the last word; for a second the room feels too small for both of you. He shakes his head with the gentleness of someone who has made a decision that aches. 'I can't,' he says. 'Not without breaking what little leverage I have left.' You let the plea dissolve into the steady tick of the clock."
        "Tell him to go, and don't guilt him":
            "You wrap an arm around yourself, steadying the urge to keep him. 'Go where you can do some good,' you say. It's both a release and a benediction. He smiles, a small, private thing, and for a moment you are grateful for that."

    # --- merge ---
    "When he leaves, you do not curse the tide. You fold the memory of him into your work like a pressed leaf. For a while the horizon feels stripped of color, but color returns in narrow"
    "bands: a volunteer's laugh as they plant; a child who learns how to nurse a sprout; Dr. Kaito's eyes, soft with old storms survived."
