    # [Scene: Shoreline After Construction | Late Afternoon]
    hide lucas_herrera
    hide amaya_saito

    scene bg ch15_771f04_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant waves thudding against concrete, gulls calling irregularly, a small hammer rhythm from the boathouse as someone repairs a bench]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm strings, rising — not triumphant, but steady and sure]
    "Narration"
    "The marsh survives in parts, not as a whole. The town has scars and small, stubborn gardens. Some families moved inland; others stayed, adapting as people always do. The fishers who once cursed the hill of"
    "concrete now chart new routes; the children learn new eddies and name new hiding places among the pilings."
    "You stand beneath the seawall and feel the shadow fall across your shoulders like a winter blanket. The seashell pendant at your throat catches the dull light and glows like a small, insistent star. You close"
    "your eyes and, for a moment, let yourself grieve the things that cannot be replanted."

    scene bg ch15_771f04_7 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft, porous thud of soil into water, volunteers whispering encouragement]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle harmonic that resolves into a single, clean note]
    "Narration"
    "You return to the boathouse. You teach the next generation how to brace a seedling's roots, how to read silt lines in the mud, how to listen to the way tides speak. You petition for small"
    "protections. You organize volunteer shifts, salvage what can be salvaged, and accept the help that comes — from neighbors, from people who once argued with you, and from strangers who come because they heard stories of"
    "a town that fought."
    "Dr. Kaito: (He rests his hand on your shoulder, voice like peat-warm tea.) 'You didn't fail the marsh, Amaya. You saved what you could. That matters enough.'"
    show amaya_saito at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "It feels small sometimes,' (You admit.) 'Like trying to stop an ocean with a bowl."
    show dr_kaito_mori at right:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kaito_mori "Then keep filling the bowl,' he says. 'One seed at a time."
    "Narration"
    "The work is not a replacement for what was lost. It is a response that insists life can be coaxed back to places meant for it. People bring seedlings with notes pinned to them. Mika arrives"
    "with a sack of mismatched rubber boots and a grin that says: tomorrow we'll make more. Volunteers plant until hands ache and cheeks shine with salt and sweat. Your notebook fills with meticulous entries again, but"
    "also with names and times and the kind of small joys that do not make headlines."
    # [Scene: The Boathouse Porch | Sunset]
    hide amaya_saito
    hide dr_kaito_mori

    scene bg ch15_771f04_8 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant laughter, the rustle of marsh reed, an evening breeze that smells of algae and promise]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A warm, ascending motif — not a resolution, but the promise of one]
    "Narration"
    "This ending is not tidy. The seawall stands; the marsh is smaller; some doors have closed. But the season turns. Saplings planted near the new channels hold; salt-tolerant grasses take, and little birds—stubborn and persistent—return to"
    "roost. You make new compacts with neighbors to steward small wetland pockets. You teach, you plant, you listen. You mourn, you remember, and you keep moving."
    "You do not stop believing that systems can change — perhaps not all at once, perhaps not before the tide takes its immediate due — but that the small, consistent work of people who stay and tend is how shorelines, and communities, begin again."

    scene bg ch15_771f04_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle choir of strings, lifting — an affirmation of continuity]
    "Narration"
    "You are disillusioned and grieving, yes. But you are also not broken. You have learned that hope is a labor, and that labor has a language: it's the names of plants written in your notebook, the schedule on the volunteer board, the steady cadence of hands in the soil."
    "You plant another clump of grass, press the roots into the mud, and watch as water takes them in. The tide may have rewritten the map, but it has not taken your will. The boathouse lamp"
    "burns late into the night; someone brings tea; someone brings a new seed catalog. You trace your finger over a patch you care for and imagine the gulls one day relearning it."

    scene bg ch15_771f04_10 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Resolve — a soft, sustained note that lingers]

    scene bg ch15_771f04_11 at full_bg
    "THE END"
